<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="363" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1250,2031]" box="[199,531,1286,1311]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1286,1311]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Description.</emphasis>
Length: 
<quantity box="[445,531,1287,1311]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.7" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" unit="mm" value="9.7">9.7 mm</quantity>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1250,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,263,1322,1347]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Head</emphasis>
: Small, bluish black, anterior glabrous, shiny, posterior punctured and wrinkled. Strongly prominent globular dark brown eyes. Labrum small, angles weakly rounded, smooth, anterior margin strongly emarginated. Clypeus smooth, with single long setae on either side, straight margin. Palpi and the lower four segments of antennae dark brown and remaining brown. Apical labial and maxillary palpomeres securiform. Mandibles fairly short, tip not crossing each other.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1250,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,320,1502,1527]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Pronotum</emphasis>
: Transverse, wider than head, bluish black, dorsal and ventral side roughly punctured and covered by yellow coloured setae, irregularly arranged large dots, Pronotal antero-lateral margin rounded with wing like expansion in the anterior half on both sides. Rounded anterior corners, posterior corners obtuse, lateral margin slightly sinuate behind the middle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1250,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,275,1646,1671]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Elytra</emphasis>
: Convex, long, weakly ovoid, greenish copper coloured, covered with yellow coloured setae, 3 times as long as pronotum; Widest behind the middle; Striae with deep punctures; Intervals weakly convex and punctured, equal in width, apex obliquely truncate and weakly emarginated; Elytral suture line not closed with a narrow gap at the apex. Projected humerus weakly sloping slightly rounded on the sides. Widest behind the middle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1250,2031]" box="[199,786,1790,1815]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1790,1815]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Scutellum</emphasis>
: triangular, dark bluish, surface glabrous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1250,2031]" box="[199,479,1826,1851]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,1826,1851]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Hind wing:</emphasis>
fully grown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1250,2031]" box="[199,564,1862,1887]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,255,1862,1887]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Legs</emphasis>
: reddish brown, pubescent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="364" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1250,2031]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,248]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="364" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1898,1923]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Remarks:</emphasis>
Pronotum is with wing like expansion in the lateromedial region and bluish black, elytra is greenish copper coloured and legs entirely reddish brown in 
<taxonomicName authority="Kollar (1836)" authorityName="Kollar" authorityYear="1836" box="[724,1031,1934,1959]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Euschizomerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticollis">
<emphasis box="[724,872,1934,1958]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">E. denticollis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[878,1031,1934,1959]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" refId="ref4098" refString="Kollar, V. (1836) Species Insectorum Coleopterorum Novae. Annalen des Wiener Museums der Naturgeschichte, 1, 327 - 336 + i - xxxi." type="journal article">Kollar (1836)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
whereas, 
<taxonomicName authority="Harold 1879" authorityName="Harold" authorityYear="1879" box="[1143,1436,1934,1959]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Euschizomerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallicus">
<emphasis box="[1143,1290,1934,1958]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">E. metallicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1296,1436,1934,1959]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" refId="ref3966" refString="Harold, E. Von (1879) Neue Coleopteren aus dem Berliner Museum. Entomologische Zeitung, Stettin, 40, 329 - 336." type="journal article">Harold 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is with lateromedial region of pronotum pointed and greenish black green in colour, dark metallic green elytra and blackish brown legs. Additionally, distinctly smaller than the 
<quantity box="[839,918,2007,2031]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" unit="mm" value="14.0">14 mm</quantity>
long 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Harold" authorityYear="1879" box="[981,1127,2006,2030]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Euschizomerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallicus">
<emphasis box="[981,1127,2006,2030]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">E. metallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Kollar (1838) provided no details of the locality of the 
<typeStatus box="[462,560,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="364">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<bibRefCitation box="[614,781,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="364" refId="ref3886" refString="Chaudoir, M. De (1878) Essai monographique sur les Panageides. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de Belgique, Bruxelles, 1879 (21), 85 - 186." type="journal article">Chaudoir 1878</bibRefCitation>
commented that it probably came from “Indes orientales”. Distribution record of 
<bibRefCitation box="[406,584,188,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="364" refId="ref3729" refString="Andrewes, H. E. (1930) Catalogue of Indian Insects. Part 18. Carabidae. Government of India Central Publication Branch, Calcutta, 388 pp." type="book">Andrewes 1930</bibRefCitation>
confirms its presence in 
<collectingCountry box="[872,930,188,213]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="364">India</collectingCountry>
(Kolkata), 
<collectingCountry box="[1061,1172,188,213]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="3" pageNumber="364">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
and in south 
<collectingCountry box="[1328,1436,188,213]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="364">East Asia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[158,265,223,248]" name="Malaysia" pageId="3" pageNumber="364">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[277,386,223,248]" name="Indonesia" pageId="3" pageNumber="364">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
- 
<collectingRegion box="[400,496,224,248]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="3" pageNumber="364">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
Island, 
<collectingCountry box="[585,706,223,248]" name="Cambodia" pageId="3" pageNumber="364">Cambodia</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
